rComments: Courtney was an ok prof overall. Her lectures were quite boring and longwinded (she basically spends the entire lecture summarizing the already boring and fairly straight forwards readings). The only interesting lecture was when she talked about indigenous rights (her speciality) as she actually seemed enthusiastic about the reading.

Personally, I found professor Jung amazing! I really enjoyed her lectures which dwelled into some very important topics. Definitely would love to take her classes again. Plus she is good at explaining thoroughly

She's a fairly non-interesting lecturer, with a very monotone voice, but has a tendency to go off on really long tangents which, while not relevant, make the lecture somewhat tolerable. However, she knows what she's talking about and is clearly passionate about politics.

Jung was a great introduction professor for politics. Her lectures were clear which made it easy to take good notes. She would discuss and explain the readings she posted. No surprises on the final exam, just analytical questions from lectures/ readings. She didn't stir controversy/ discussions but gave solid lectures. I would recommend her.

she's big on posting all readings, which are about 40 pages every week. if you do readings, then u dont need to go to lectures. Her lectures are informative, and she's pretty funny, and talks to students afterwards. Really enjoys teaching and cares about students. Syllabus actually helps structure thinking, good foundation

I really want to like Prof. Jung, but I can't. Lectures are consistently dry, usually a regurgitation of the reading. Readings are UBER long, half of them are tangential to the topic at hand. Doesn't provide clear guidelines for tests or assessments. She seems like an interesting person to talk politics with, but that's it.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Get ready to read', 'Lecture heavy']

rComments: I had her for both POL101Y and POL201Y. None required textbooks, she posts notes. You can tell she actually enjoys what she's teaching. Plus she knows what she's talking about. She's humble enough to accept a correction or suggestions from students. Her humour needs getting used to but you'll be laughing with her by the end. All around great prof!
teacherRatingTags: ['Get ready to read', "Skip class? You won't pass.", 'Amazing lectures']

rComments: A little boring.
she watered down all the materials and left us with overly simplified understanding of the material covered

I wanted to like her but she just isn't a good lecturer. She's chill though so chill that she wrote the exam last minute and made it super easy. I like that she doesn't take things too seriously unlike Professor Hansen, she also has a good fashion sense which is rare at U of T
teacherRatingTags: ['So many papers', 'Get ready to read', 'Accessible outside class']

rComments: Interesting material, boring delivery.

Professor Jung was a very interesting professor to learn from this year. Some often argue that her voice can be monotonous, but she often repeats key information SEVERAL times in lectures, which is most helpful when making notes. Overall, I thoroughly enjoyed her class and would recommend to others!

The curriculum is interesting and all the readings are available online which saves you money but the prof herself is pretty terrible. Her lectures are just 2 hour summaries of the text (which she often forgets) or just answering inaudible questions in Con Hall. Not a bad class but skipping the lectures made it much more bearable.
Interesting course, the readings can be very boring. Papers require lots of source + work.
teacherRatingTags: ["Skip class? You won't pass.", 'So many papers', 'Get ready to read']

rComments: She basically reads the text but can sometimes be intriguing. Go to class, read the texts and you'll be good. PLUS is that there is NO textbook, she posts the readings online which is really helpful and you save money.

She was simply amazing , took her course 4 years ago and since graduated . But did a fantastic job at explaining theories, concepts, ideas . In addition offered her own analysis with supporting evidence . Politics of development is the most enlightening course at the Political science department . She really keeps students engaged by provoking thou

Professor Jung was very kind, she answered many questions in class and was helped me personally when I asked her a question via email. The course was not hard, the lecture usually covered the weeks readings so I often skipped the readings and attended lectures, after all that way I knew what she found important. Hope to have her again!
I liked her but I think she may be a communist. Great class and very interesting to be taught from such an unorthodox perspective

Great lecturer with passion and enthusiasm for the material. Does a great job going out of her way to answer as many students' questions as she can. I had no knowledge of any of the material in this class prior to enrolment and now that it is finished not only did I learn so much valuable insight into the field, but I am more engaged than ever!

This class is not easy but it will make you think critically and you will therefore be a MUCH better student because of it. Professor Jung is tough and the assignments are graded harshly. That being said, go get your ciuccio if you're not up for the challenge otherwise buck up and stop whining

She sounds like a high school student when she talks "like..." She does not sound like an intellectualprofessor. The course is a baby course, attend lectures, do homework and so on. Welcome to high school. Just do the readings and you'll be fine for exams, no need to attend her lectures. also the weekly discussion board is highly annoying

Courtney Jung taught one of the best courses I ever had in all my four years. Taking this course changed my life. She gave us so many ideas to think about and analyzed them so thoroughly that I feel like I grew intellectually from her so much. If I had never took this course, I would be missing out on a life-changing experience.

I liked this class.  Her lectures were a bit dry but I actually really appreciated having someone who felt compelled to talk about the material, rather than make glib jokes.  She was always clear on what we were supposed to do with our assignments.  Good prof.
She adds nothing to the readings, but to be fair, she's super clear. Midterm and finals are a walk in the park.

Prof. Jung knows the general material well, but mostly summarizes readings, which is actually helpful for the exam as you don't really need to read the material if you can't get to it. Overall, it's a good course although she does speak too fast.. when asked to repeat something she's surprised that you didn't catch it the first time.

Courtney Jung is an inspiration. Although the class is not what it was supposed to be, I have learned so much and she has taught us such interesting things and has changed the way I look at the world. She has made me want to major in politics and I am incredibly excited to learn she'll be teaching my developmental politics class next year! :)
speaks to fast. and she only summarizes the reading for lecture which is long and brutal. the course name doesn't go with the actual content of lecture. it's more development and economy

The name of the course is misleading, since she's not Canadian and doesn't specialize in Canadian politics. Instead it's on democracy and development, which is much more interesting. My only issue with her class is that there's no additional insight on what we've read, and the lecture is simply a summary of the reading. Still too early to judge tho

Speaks too quickly and does not repeat anything. She expects you to already know everything she is saying, so what is she teaching? I have no idea! Especially since the course is called "Political Science - Canada in Comparative Perspective" and it has nothing to do with politics, or Canada. So what am I paying for? Something I didn't want...
